I was halfway through with my meal, and wanted to express my sincerest gratitude to the employees of this restaurant. I'm glad I waited until afterwards, as the food would have been too cold before I was capable of finishing. They were exquisitely kind and thorough in explaining the menu, helping me choose the perfect meal for me (although after much fuss I did arrive at my regular meal of Chicken Tikka Masala). The food was prepared exquisitely to order, using only the finest halal ingredients. I wanted for nothing throughout the entire experience, and was truly treated as family by my standards. I eat Indian food frequently, and often order the Chicken Tikka Masala so that I can compare which restaurant has the best. After today, I can safely say I'm never going to have Chicken Tikka Masala prepared quite as well again. I think I might have to switch to a new dish when I order Indian food again in the future, as nothing else will compare to this experience.

I would give zero stars if I could. The guy waiting our table was incredibly condescending and rude 1.  We asked for lemon slices to go along with our kebabs and he suggested we borrow them from the ones they served with chicken biriyani that was someone else's on the table.  2. We requested that the rice provided with the curries(by default) be changed to naan. He refused. His reasoning was that rice is easier to cook than naan, so we couldn't  swap. Not only that, we did not even get the rice that was supposed to come with the curries in the first place.  3. He advised us to keep our wallets and phones in our pockets instead of table so that he could keep food - there were two on the table in a group of 10.  4. The food was super bland. Chicken curry ("Chicken Vindaloo") had over boiled, stringy chicken and undercooked potatoes. The gravy had a distinct taste of canned tomatoes.  5. Chicken Kadai was also the same. Over boiled chicken and tasteless.  6. Vegetable biriyani was an abomination. Bland rice with boiled vegetables and no spices. An extra small cup of raita(curd) cost us 1.99 dollars. No Indian restaurant charges that amount.  7. They destroyed tea. We ordered masala chai (spiced tea) and it had no spices whatsoever.  The Rogan Josh tasted nothing like what it is supposed to, but was edible. The kebab platter was also edible. The naan was soft. That are the only saving Grace in an otherwise sad and disappointing meal.

We were driving from Niagara falls to NYC and our GPS indicated that there is an Indian restaurant by the interstate. When we arrived at the address the place looked very unattractive for a some passing by to go in. Not surprisingly we were the only customer in the not so well lighted place. The owner who was working as waiter/cook was nice and he gave us some insight about the area. We took his recommendation and ordered chicken biryani. It turned out to be great. We will recommend this place for friends and family.

Food is cooked in home made style and not the typical restaurant style Indian food.  I highly recommend this restaurant.  Food at this restaurant is better than most places on Devon Street in Chicago.  Chappati (roti) is handmade fresh.  Highly recommended! great food at low prices.
